The paper deals with privacy-preserving distributed computation, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. The use of differential privacy suggests that the paper may belong to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) or cs.LG (Machine Learning), as these sub-categories often deal with privacy-preserving techniques. The problem of iterative consensus is a classic problem in distributed computing, which suggests that the paper may also belong to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The use of randomized mechanisms and the establishment of tradeoffs between privacy and accuracy suggest that the paper may also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory) or cs.SY (Systems and Control).
